        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3891385490" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14901207186346341206">The book is an inspiring read about how we should have faith.<br/><br/>But the book has elements which some readers may find objectionable. The biggest is the promotion of ecumenicalism: though many of the major characters are Protestant, four main characters are devout Catholics (including two priests, one of whom worked for the Vatican investigating causes for sainthood; it is implied that Sara would be considered for sainthood if she were a Catholic) and the book seems to indicate that there are no maj</span>
  <span id="freeText14901207186346341206" style="display:none">The book is an inspiring read about how we should have faith.<br /><br />But the book has elements which some readers may find objectionable. The biggest is the promotion of ecumenicalism: though many of the major characters are Protestant, four main characters are devout Catholics (including two priests, one of whom worked for the Vatican investigating causes for sainthood; it is implied that Sara would be considered for sainthood if she were a Catholic) and the book seems to indicate that there are no major differences between the groups (which many Protestants would find disagreeable). Also some of the characters use profanity and alcohol.<br /><br />As such I knocked off one star.<br /><br />NOTE: The book was made into a faith-based movie, The Girl Who Believes In Miracles, which came out on Easter Weekend 2021. The objectionable elements were removed (though the movie added a couple of its own). Though nowhere near a box-office smash if you can find it on a streaming service I recommend it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14901207186346341206" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

